selectedmemories.Title: Last Year's Man
selectedmemories.description: I listened to this song often on the journey to high school during an unseasonably warm September. That summer I had just discovered Leonard Cohen's music and was enchanted.  I shared the albums I obsessed over during the holiday with someone I started dating when the school term began. I remember once after school we sat in a park atop a big hill and listened to this song on wired headphones we split, nestled under  our jackets we'd prop up over some sticks for shade.

selectedmemories.Title: Money, Money, Money
selectedmemories.description: Moving to England from Sri Lanka with my family. My uncle picking us up at the airport and driving us to his family's home. My cousin asking me if I know what a television is. Me replying I don't know. Seeing a television set for the first time.

selectedmemories.Title: Roslyn
selectedmemories.description: I was sitting in my friend Amy's car, late at night, right before she was about to drive me home for the evening. We had spent the night playing billiards in her parent's house and being in a hot-tub under the stars, and I was probably a bit or a lot in love. The song came on and we sat there in her driveway looking at the sky, in that kind of quiet that exists only that late at night as you can feel there is a sense of an ending.

selectedmemories.Title: Baby Beluga
selectedmemories.description: Sitting in the back of my mom's green Volkswagen station wagon as she drives me and my best friend to dance class, my mom is singing along to the music

selectedmemories.Title: You've Got a Friend
selectedmemories.description: This was a song that I frequently listened to during a difficult time in my childhood.  My father had died and my mother was terminally ill. I would listen to the song in our living room which was the only room that had a stereo. I would be alone. I would play the entire album repeatedly which had a number of songs that I identified with and that provided comfort to me. The songs helped me understand what I was going through and gave me hope.
selectedmemories.emoextra: despair, contentedness, affirming, empathy, hopeful, optimism

selectedmemories.Title: Pink + White
selectedmemories.description: This memory occurred on a trip to Sri Lanka. After traveling from the US to Sri Lanka I had just got into a van hired to take us to our hotel. My family, including my Dad, Mom, and sister were there. As we drove from the airport to our hotel I played the album Blonde and remember listening to Pink + White while looking at the palm trees outside the car.

selectedmemories.Title: Izzo (H.O.V.A.)
selectedmemories.description: It was in 2001 and I was on the train to somewhere with my big brother after having weeks earlier emigrated to the UK. My big bro who had lived in the UK for a couple years prior put his over ear headphones on my ears and told me to "listen to this". This was the first hip hop song I had ever heard and I loved. It spawned a deep love and affinity to this music and suffice to say was quite a formative moment.

selectedmemories.Title: Wake Me Up Before You Go-Go
selectedmemories.description: Reminds me of my younger days, in school, and listening to the song - dancing, singing, and overall having no stress and enjoying life.

selectedmemories.Title: Moondance - 2013 Remaster
selectedmemories.description: In college I was in an a cappella singing group and this song was my solo my freshman year. I have fond memories of singing it with my friends and group mates in our rehearsal room, college chapel, brick steps under the bridge to our art museum on campus, at other college performance halls and on stage.

selectedmemories.Title: Terrible Love
selectedmemories.description: This song was playing in the car when my brother and best friend were dropping me off at the Seattle-Tacoma airport for me to fly to Geneva, Switzerland for a 4 month study abroad. It was a cloudy morning with a little bit of misting rain. I was sitting in the front passenger seat. I had just broken up with my boyfriend two days prior, and I recall missing him, being very sad to leave all my friends, and fairly anxious/nervous about the logistics of my travel and the upcoming semester.

selectedmemories.Title: Pump It Up
selectedmemories.description: At boarding school, on days with heavy snow we were expected to get up early and shovel snow around campus before going to classes. I would blast this song to wake people up. My room was on the third floor, I can remember the physical environment: hallways and stairwell, doors, etc. but less so who was in each room. Memory happened over several years, so maybe that is why only the consistent environmental elements are there

selectedmemories.Title: Iris
selectedmemories.description: Iris by the Goo Goo Dolls reminds me of early adolescent summer camp dances. Each dance had three slow dances and Iris was one of the tracks selected. The song reminds me of the carefree years of middle school where my biggest concern was whether I would slow dance with my crush (I did).

selectedmemories.Title: Vellai Pura Ondru (Solo)
selectedmemories.Artist: Artist: K. J. Yesudas Movie: Pudhu Kavithai (Tamil)
selectedmemories.description: This was a song my dad used to play in our first home.

selectedmemories.Title: Running Up That Hill (A Deal With God)
selectedmemories.description: I was in the backseat of a car with 3 friends and my boyfriend. We were on holiday in France and driving through the countryside to a bakery. My friend turned on the radio and this song was playing. I remember looking at the surrounding area and fields and feeling content.

selectedmemories.Title: You Send Me
selectedmemories.description: It reminds me of a time in my life a few years ago with an ex-partner, I sort of remember it being at their house but I guess it's an overall feeling, we used to sing it a lot together, and a specific memory of walking home late at night under building works singing it together and felt a lot of love for each other.
selectedmemories.emoextra: love, appreciation, serenity, mutual affection, empathy, trust, understanding

selectedmemories.Title: Summer Nights - From вЂњGreaseвЂќ
selectedmemories.description: It is a summer's day and I am leaving my house alone to walk to school. I am singing this song to myself and I remember it being the first time that year I can leave the house without a jacket. I relish the warmth and novelty of a warm summer's day in England. I don't believe the memory is because of the song's title - just that it was a very popular song at the time.

selectedmemories.Title: The Ash Grove
selectedmemories.description: This song was sung regularly at the summer camp for girls I attended in my teen years. It was often sung in the closing circle ceremony at the end of the day and was sung in beautiful harmony by the 100 or so girl campers.

selectedmemories.Title: It's All Coming Back to Me Now
selectedmemories.description: I remember my mum playing this in the car in summer. I remember she was a Celine Dion fan, so this was one of the tapes which got played a lot as I rode around with her, my brother and sister.

selectedmemories.Title: Jika Sempat
selectedmemories.description: I remember the song specifically with the memory of being in a music studio and with a band of my friends practicing the song for an upcoming performance for an event by a society in university. I was sitting at the side, listening in and giving feedback as I was the director. I remember feeling emotional trying to envision how great the song would be on stage, and because it was on valentines, I was also overwhelmed with emotion as I was developing feelings for a friend in the band.

selectedmemories.Title: Closing Time
selectedmemories.description: I was at a dance on the last night of a summer reading camp that I attended during high school.  I was with the whole camp, specifically dancing with other girls in my "pod".  The camp was at Amherst College.  It was one of the happiest times of my life and this was the last song on the last night, so when I left the next day I listened to the song on repeat and cried.

selectedmemories.Title: Starships
selectedmemories.description: A youth group sleepover with one of my best friends at the time (and other youth) in a church we hadn't visited before. All full of sugar from sweeties and wanted to jump around and be loud so we put on Nicki Minaj Starships while in our jammies and sleeping bags and had a proper wee boogie.

selectedmemories.Title: Use Somebody
selectedmemories.description: First year university, near the end of the year- dancing at a club (downstairs on the corner) in Gastown with the European group from 4th floor. I was with Peter and Thomas, we all started singing together in a circle when this song came on.

selectedmemories.Title: Just the Girl
selectedmemories.description: I remember being in the car with my mother, sister, and uncle when this song played on the radio. I was really enjoying this song when my mother asked my uncle to turn it off.

selectedmemories.Title: Miss You
selectedmemories.description: I was driving home from my best friend's house of that time. We used to spend a lot of time together, nearly dated, were very close. This song reminds me of the foggy autumn evenings of my home in Austria, the tranquillity of driving in the dark and of the numerous wonderful days spent with my friend.

selectedmemories.Title: Pulsewidth
selectedmemories.description: Was spring first year of university, smoking cigarettes with a close friend watching the sun rise as we pulled an all-nighter for exam revision. We set up some kitchen chairs outside and listened to the track through some speakers.

selectedmemories.Title: Come Healing
selectedmemories.description: I first heard the song while watching the movie "The Farewell," and was quite struck by it. I'd just gone through a breakup. About a week later, the world shut down due to Covid. The song stuck with me, so much so that soon after, I began to teach it to myself on guitar and played it every night for a year while living at home with my parents and dog again. I still play it, though with not as much frequency, at it brings back both happy and sad memories.

selectedmemories.Title: Take a Chance on Me
selectedmemories.description: I was at a JLS concert and one of the band members sat on the edge of the stage and sang this song to a couple of us. I was around 14 and with one of my friends at the concert.

selectedmemories.Title: Paranoid Android
selectedmemories.description: Visiting my girlfriend at university for the weekend. We were sitting in her bedroom and playing each other music that we liked. I played Radiohead, it was the first time she had heard the band and she really liked their passion.

selectedmemories.Title: January
selectedmemories.description: Secondary School discos in 1977 ~ cold and dark. Very dodgy outfits and lots of dancing in circles around handbags. Nervous anticipation about being asked to dance or worse still not!

selectedmemories.Title: Yellow
selectedmemories.description: It was 2000, and the Leonid meteor shower was passing over the UK - my two friends came over for a sleepover and we lay on the lawn outside most of the night watching the shooting stars. We were all heavily into the Parachutes album at that point and were singing 'Yellow'. It was a really lovely, otherworldly, comradely night, I remember it being cold and damp and dewy on the grass but not minding at all. We had probably had a couple of drinks! The song always reminds me of that night.

selectedmemories.Title: Strawberry Swing
selectedmemories.description: I was with my first boyfriend. We didn't have much in common- but his favourite song was Strawberry Swing. I used to listen to it to calm me down when I missed him, normally before bed. It was a caring song that comforted me a lot. It still brings me a lot of peace now, even after our relationship went sour.

selectedmemories.Title: Ride of the Valkyries
selectedmemories.description: I was in my childhood home, watching my little brother race around the table as soon as we put the song on.  I was with my parents.

selectedmemories.Title: Bicycle Race
selectedmemories.description: It always reminds me of visiting my grandparents. My parents always used to play Queen's Greatest Hits in the car on the way there, and it was the song that I most looked forward to hearing.

selectedmemories.Title: Losing My Religion
selectedmemories.description: I remember going to family functions and the band would play this song all the time

selectedmemories.Title: You Make Me Feel So Young
selectedmemories.description: We had frank sinatra - you make me feel so young for our first dance at our wedding. My husband and I were dancing in the middle of the dance floor surrounded by people we loved, celebrating our wedding.

selectedmemories.Title: Rocket Man (I Think It's Going To Be A Long, Long Time)
selectedmemories.description: I was at an outdoor music event with my friends, dancing in the darkness.

selectedmemories.Title: I Don't Want to Miss a Thing - From "Armageddon" Soundtrack
selectedmemories.description: This song was used for the first dance at my wedding.  It takes me straight back to dancing with my new wife with all our friends and family around us.

selectedmemories.Title: a thousand years
selectedmemories.description: I was at home and I was holding my cat, Imogen. I started singing this song to her. I could see that it was relaxing her. She started purring and then fell asleep.

selectedmemories.Title: Lost on You
selectedmemories.description: First time when I heard this song I was in Italy in Venice with my partner and I heard it so many times when I was walking on the streets in different cities from Italy, so always when I hear this song it reminds me about these happy times I had there in Italy.

selectedmemories.Title: I'm Just a Kid
selectedmemories.description: I remember hanging out at a friend's house getting ready to throw a party. It was a summer afternoon and we were going to have a lot of people over at their house. We all started singing this song and it really got us in the mood for the party. Every time I hear this song it reminds me of that day, because it brings me back to a time when I did not have a care in the world. It makes me feel like I had nothing to worry about and just got to enjoy life.

selectedmemories.Title: Born in the U.S.A.
selectedmemories.description: Being in a cafe in Donegal, with my future wife. It was a sunny day, and the cafe were playing this, it was the summer (probably August) of 1985, the town was possibly Glencolmcille

selectedmemories.Title: Ticket To Ride - Remastered 2009
selectedmemories.description:
I remember being really young when I first heard this song. Maybe I was 8 or 9 years old, and I remember playing with my brother and then hearing this song on my mother's radio coming from the kitchen.
+D45
I loved the song straight away and me and my brother were dancing that day.

selectedmemories.Title: Fake Plastic Trees
selectedmemories.description: I feel I listened to this song when I had stress and mayhem in my life and just wanted peace and I was on my own and sitting by myself. I think the song is very melodic and soothing and I thought things cannot be so bad and if I can feel calm in that moment just from listening to a song, then I can apply this to my life as I think life does not have to be full of stress there is good and everything is not always bad and I have to be mindful and think in the moment.

selectedmemories.Title: Love Will Keep Us Together
selectedmemories.description: Was a really young kid, like 3 years old, and driving with my mom to the store in Laguna beach. The windows were down and the weather was nice. We got to the store and everything was in clear plexiglass display cases. She bought me a toy. I remember there being lots of eucalyptus which smelled really nice. After we shopped, I got my hair cut at Rudy's barber shop and was afraid he was going to accidentally cut my ear again as he had done before. It was a great day with my mom.

selectedmemories.Title: Making Your Mind Up
selectedmemories.description: It takes me back to being about 4 years old and singing it in front of my family. I remember everyone clapping and cheering as I was giving my best dance moves. It's always been referred to as my song ever since.

selectedmemories.Title: Touch Me In The Morning
selectedmemories.description: This song reminds me of when I said goodbye to someone I loved. He was leaving to live in another country and myself and a group of friends went to say goodbye as he was leaving. This happened at university.

selectedmemories.Title: I Want to Know What Love Is - 1999 Remaster
selectedmemories.description: It was cold outside and I was walking my dog. I was 15 years old. I had just bought a Sony Walkman and I was listening to the song. I realized how cool music can be and I enjoyed the audio quality of the new Walkman. I just remember being immersed in the song and realizing the profound impact music and songs can have.

selectedmemories.Title: Breaking the Habit
selectedmemories.description: Being at home at my parents house. After school talking to friends online. Playing video games and listening to music at the same time. Using myspace as social media. Lounging on a bean bag.

selectedmemories.Title: Sugar, We're Goin Down
selectedmemories.description: I remember hanging out with a friend named Kim. We were walking around the mall and just so happened to bump into Cameron. We were just store hopping not actually shopping. We walk into this one store called Spenser's. The song just comes on and Cameron starts to jam out. I just remember hearing the drums right away and my ears perk out, I was so invested with the song that it is my go-to song.

selectedmemories.Title: Yesterday Once More
selectedmemories.description: I was in the car with my parents and brother. I can't remember where we are going but I remember my mum was singing. It was a happy moment.

selectedmemories.Title: Pretty (Ugly Before)
selectedmemories.description: I was lying in bed during summer and talking to someone at the time who I ended up becoming romantically involved with. I just remember this song washing over me and giving me a strong sense of confidence.

selectedmemories.Title: I'm Still Standing
selectedmemories.description: It was Christmas day. Myself and my two sisters had bought the album for my Dad for Christmas. We were playing on a new computer set up right in the middle of the living room and this album was on and this is the song we all knew and sang and danced and were happy to.

selectedmemories.Title: Tondo
selectedmemories.description: This is a song that reminds me of when I went to go and see Folamour perform live. It was my favourite song out of the whole set and took me a long time to track down the name of the song and find it online.

selectedmemories.Title: The Final Countdown
selectedmemories.description: This song always brings back memories of my childhood, it was the first real song I like and always remember it being played in the kitchen of my family home.

selectedmemories.Title: Triumph
selectedmemories.description:
J Hus - Triumph is a song from the album 'Big Conspiracy'. This album came out during lockdown in 2020 and I listened to the whole album daily while I was working. Triumph for some reason is the song which reminds me most about that time even though it's not my favourite song on the album.

It reminds me of a time when a lot of things were going on in the world, however it evokes positive emotions from a simpler time.

selectedmemories.Title: Fix You
selectedmemories.description: I went to my first ever gig which was Coldplay and I drove from my hometown to Bolton to get there. It took several hours and I went with my then girlfriend. I was a big Coldplay fan and it was the biggest car journey I'd done myself since passing my test too. I remember that fix you was the last song and it was used in the music video too, which went on to be a massive hit.

selectedmemories.Title: Music Sounds Better With You
selectedmemories.description: This song came out in 1998, and it reminds me of playing football outside on a sunny day during the summer with my friends.

selectedmemories.Title: Superheroes
selectedmemories.description: I was listening to this song a lot during a specific time period in college and whilst listening to this specific song I had found out from a group that my business teacher (who was my favourite) had suddenly died which was a huge shock. Whenever I hear the song, I instantly think of that scene and the teacher.

selectedmemories.Title: Follow Me - Club Mix
selectedmemories.description: My first time in Ibiza, surrounded by my closest friends. It reminds me of a time where I was carefree, enjoying life and having fun and laughs with my friends before we had children and responsibilities, it makes me feel happy and proud of living my life to the fullest.

selectedmemories.Title: Children
selectedmemories.description: The memory that I associate with this is being on holiday at the pool. It was the first time I had heard this song and it made me instantly feel like I was in a dream. The song really connected with me and made me feel relaxed and happy. Whilst the song played we were jumping in the pool and having a really good time. I didn't initially know what the song was til a later date.

selectedmemories.Title: Unfinished Sympathy
selectedmemories.description: My favourite song in university. I overplayed it considerably and eventually sort of forgot about it. Years later, I moved by myself to another country, it was a lonely experience, and I struggled a few weeks. One Friday evening, I went out to a bar and was pondering if I should move back home again when the song started playing, the happy memories flooded in, I ended up talking to a group of other expats who were also in the bar and we became friends, I stayed in the country for years.

selectedmemories.Title: January, February
selectedmemories.description: This song reminds me of being a very small child and being very close with my mother at home. It brings feelings of happiness, innocence, and security whenever I hear it.

selectedmemories.Title: ruiner
selectedmemories.description: This song reminds me of a previous breakup I went through. It reminds me of a girlfriend I had for almost two years who I mutually broke up with because we no longer saw things the same. It was a major let-down for me as I truly loved her, and I am convinced she felt the same. I listened to this song a lot throughout this time and it without fail reminds me of the hurt I felt.

selectedmemories.Title: Lovesong
selectedmemories.description: This song reminds me of the boy I loved. However, we met at the wrong time in our lives and we couldn't be together. Every time I hear this song, I remember when we were sitting on a park bench and looking at each other, knowing that tomorrow we had to part and that it would be the biggest mistake of our lives. And it was a mistake, but there was no other way.

selectedmemories.Title: Count To Six And Die (The Vacuum Of Infinite Space Encompassing)
selectedmemories.description: I listened to this particular track on repeat when I realized my first marriage was all but over. It was a sheer realization after a particularly nasty argument with him at our little apartment where we lived; it felt like something breaking inside me. I seriously considered killing myself: I was in a foreign country, I had absolutely nothing, and I'd be going back to my homeland to more nothing since my own family didn't want me back. It was the end of the dream I had fought so hard for.

selectedmemories.Title: Mr. Brightside
selectedmemories.description: This was one of my favourite songs when I was growing up. I went to see the band at a gig in 2007 in London, with my two best friends.

selectedmemories.Title: Walk Like an Egyptian
selectedmemories.description: Walk like an Egyptian was a top song of 1987, I think. This was played all the time on the radio when I was a young kid and I can remember this song being played on the TV show Top of the Pops. In the music video the people made the classic Egyptian walk movement. I can remember having a birthday party and this song was played and me, my friends and family did the walk like an Egyptian walk. I can still remember it now and it often reminds me of that time when I hear that song now. A great song.

selectedmemories.Title: Tonight (I'm Lovin' You)
selectedmemories.description: I used to listen to this song while driving to school and work. I would listen to it anywhere I went like shopping etc, mostly with my sisters. It was such a carefree time of my life, just having fun, driving fast listening to this song.

selectedmemories.Title: Wish You Were Here-1
selectedmemories.description: Following completion of 6th form at school, me and my friend went on a 2-week tour of Western European countries by car. I distinctly recall this song being played on the car cassette when we were traversing through the Alps. For me this song perfectly encapsulated the environment that we were in and always brings this memory whenever I hear the song anywhere such as YouTube.

selectedmemories.Title: Cornerstone
selectedmemories.description: This song evokes thanksgiving and joy in me whenever I listen to it since my 40th birthday. It brings back memories of childhood looking forward to becoming an adult.

selectedmemories.Title: Shine
selectedmemories.description: My husband had left me and my two children, 1 and 4 year olds. I had no job, the house to pay for and the children to bring up. He left for another woman, and he didn't pay towards his children or see them regularly. This was my song that gave me hope for the future. I am now very happily married to the love of my life and my children have grown into successful adults.

selectedmemories.Title: What's New Pussycat?
selectedmemories.description: I used to sing "What's New Pussycat" to one of my cats. She fell ill and the surgery intended to save her ended up doing more harm than good. I sang it to her again at the veterinary hospital before she was euthanized. Whenever I hear the words or tune, I think of her.

selectedmemories.Title: Hey Jude - Remastered 2015
selectedmemories.description: I was 14 years old and I was waiting to hear the first playing of the new single by my favourite group, The Beatles. I knew it was going to be played on the BBC radio at 1o'clock and so as it was a sunny day I tied my portable radio to the front of my pushbike and went for a ride alone on a track across the South Downs overlooking Brighton where I lived. I can still picture myself being amazed by the song and by the end I stopped riding my bike and had to just sit and listen to it. It was amazing.

selectedmemories.Title: Coffee
selectedmemories.description: I see freshman year in Chapel Hill - HoJo specifically. I don't have many friends and I don't like my roommate, but I randomly bump into a group of people one night on my way to the lounge who immediately become my best friends. They love my laugh, they love my Adventure Time shirt, they love me. After class, we'd all hang in Liam and Ahmed's room and listen to Sylvan Esso's debut album on repeat and eat tons of dining hall cookies.

selectedmemories.Title: Close to You
selectedmemories.description: I was still at school and dating a boy from the same school. I was becoming very fond of him and I was at home with my parents one day when I heard this song on the radio. I knew then that I wanted to be close to him always. We've been married for 48 years.

selectedmemories.Title: Smoke on the Water
selectedmemories.description: It was one of the first gigs I ever attended and my favourite songs. I was with my best mate. It brings back strong memories of independence and youth and enjoyment.

selectedmemories.Title: Bang A Gong (Get It On) (Electric Version)
selectedmemories.description: This song was around the year I was 14 or 15 and during the summer I had a lot of freedom and remember hearing this song all the time. My friends loved it too and we used to sing it together. We used to meet at a weir pool and play T Rex music and go swimming. Later in the summer I had a bad stomach bug due to swimming in the dirty water and was confined to bed but still listened to this music.

selectedmemories.Title: Oops Up Side Your Head - 12" Single Version
selectedmemories.description:
My best friend and I had a joint 21st birthday party at a local nightclub. It was late 1980's and we went to the club every weekend. The outside of it was where they filmed the outside of Fawlty Towers, so it was called Fawlty's. We had a great night & loads of family & friends came.
Oops Upside your head came on and everyone got onto the floor and sat in rows behind each other and did the usual dance to the song with each of us at the head of a line

selectedmemories.Title: Liar - Remastered 2011
selectedmemories.description: I was watching The Old Grey Whistle test on BBC at home late at night. My mother was in bed I just fell in love with the singer I was probably about 15 then. Mesmerising I couldn't take my eyes off him and that's probably how my love for music started. No one had heard of the band then, my school friends hadn't or record shop where I went to order LP Queen

selectedmemories.Title: Sweet Child O' Mine
selectedmemories.description: I was with one of my closest friends. We were on a short break by the seaside and we were staying in a hotel that had MTV. It was a good break.

selectedmemories.Title: Sealed With A Kiss
selectedmemories.description: It was in the 70s. I was holidaying with my friend Susan and her family. We were camping in a large family tent on a campsite called Reighton Sands. It was a very hot summer; we were in our teens so we could wander around the campsite freely. We would go in the clubhouse a lot, the kids clubroom had a jukebox, they had this record in it (sealed with a kiss) and I would play it every time.

selectedmemories.Title: Yesterday Once More
selectedmemories.description: I was about 10 years old, it was summer we would take a radio to our local park with my friends and would all sing along when we heard this song, there was a young girl from London visiting her grandmother for the summer, when I hear this song I remember her.

selectedmemories.Title: First Time Ever I Saw Your Face with Jools Holland Orchestra - Decade In The Sun Version
selectedmemories.description: It was the music for the first dance at my wedding. It evokes wonderful memories of my wedding day, the smile that never left my husband's face, the joy of the occasion and having all my friends and family around me - some of whom are no longer with us.

selectedmemories.Title: Where Do Broken Hearts Go
selectedmemories.description: My mum and dad both loved listening to my niece singing this when she was young. Sadly, they both died too soon and my niece recorded the song which was played at both of their funerals. Now when I hear this song played it upsets me so much even though it has good memories of Happy times it also gives me great sadness too.

selectedmemories.Title: We Are The Champions - Remastered 2011
selectedmemories.description: I was in a dead-end job and hadn't even realised I was being bullied by my boss every day. I saw a much more interesting job advertised, applied, and got it. I sang this song in my head relentlessly after I got the phone call.

selectedmemories.Title: Puppet On A String
selectedmemories.description: I remember playing this song frequently around my sixth birthday and insisting it was used for all the musical games such as musical statues, musical bumps and pass the parcel at my sixth birthday party. I had my school friends at the party which took place at the family home.

selectedmemories.Title: Suburbia
selectedmemories.description: It's more a general memory of when I was at 6th form college. We were all just old enough to be served in pubs without being challenged and this was a song that seemed to be constantly played in one of the pubs near college. Pub quiz machines were becoming popular and because my group of friends were studying a variety of subjects and had a variety of interests, we used to regularly win large amounts of money. The song seems to go with the sound of Ј1 coins hitting the tray.

selectedmemories.Title: Every Little Thing She Does Is Magic
selectedmemories.description: It was at my sister's birthday party and I was responsible for putting on the music. I put this on because it is a good song and it reminded me of one of the friends of my sister which I liked and she was at the party and she was dancing.

selectedmemories.Title: High
selectedmemories.description: It was a song me and my then partner at the time choose as our future wedding song, it brings back many memories of being married young, the anniversaries of listening to the song and still when I hear it 26 years later, it takes me back to that time when I was married and the things we did whilst married.

selectedmemories.Title: Love Don't Live Here Anymore
selectedmemories.description: I remember as a girl this song being on the radio whilst I had breakfast. I was on a breakfast stool sitting at the bar in the kitchen eating Ready Brek. I don't like Ready Brek so I recall this song and the dislike of the cereal at the same time! This would be in the mid to late 70's in my childhood home.

selectedmemories.Title: Hey Jude
selectedmemories.description: I was fairly young and listening to this record, with my sisters, at my parents' house. We were sitting in our front room where the record player was, and my eldest sister put this record on. At first, I didn't particularly like it but after my sister played it a few times, I found it quite haunting and started to come round to it. I had previously thought that I had bought the record but on reflection, I think my sister did.

selectedmemories.Title: Something's Gotten Hold Of My Heart
selectedmemories.description:
In my bedroom alone, sitting at my dressing table getting ready to go out that night. It was a Saturday, and I was meeting my boyfriend in the city. I'd bought this record earlier that day and played it over and over on my portable record player that mum and dad had bought me for my birthday.
I think the repeated playing of it drove my parents mad, but they didn't say anything.

selectedmemories.Title: One Love / People Get Ready
selectedmemories.description: In our household the song was played a lot and when Bob Marley died, that song was played a lot on the radio over a long period of time. Jamaicans love that song and sing it a lot at parties.

selectedmemories.Title: Bohemian Rhapsody
selectedmemories.description: This song was a Number 1 hit on the pop charts in the UK for what seemed like weeks, if I recall correctly. It reminds me of being in high school/secondary school. My friends and I liked the song. At the end of the school term, classes were a bit more relaxed; we had P.E in the gym but the teacher left the class alone playing ball games. It was very loud with everyone shouting and laughing, and my best friend and I sat at the side and for some reason started singing Bohemian Rhapsody out loud.
selectedmemories.emoextra: Friendship and bonding, sharing something that made us both laugh because of the unusual lyrics in the song.

selectedmemories.Title: I'm Not In Love
selectedmemories.description: It was in the charts the year I met my husband; it was 1975 and life was good. Daniel was my first proper boyfriend and I thought he was fab and so good looking, and he was my new boyfriend. We went to the local pub in the side room where all the younger people hung out and this record was playing on the jukebox. This track always takes me back to that year and how happy I was. We are no longer together and there are things I regret, and this song always reminds me of Daniel.

selectedmemories.Title: Ghost Town
selectedmemories.description: I remember the UK events in 1981. Widespread unemployment, inner city riots and just a general feeling of despondency amongst the adults. I was still a child and living with my parents at home in Salford.

selectedmemories.Title: Return to Sender
selectedmemories.description: This is the first record I bought with my own money.  I also bought it on the way to see a friend which involved taking a bus to a strange town for the first time alone. I was 13/14 and felt very grown up although I'm sure I wasn't. This was also unusual as I was never a big Elvis fan, more if a Beatles girl. When I hear this song it takes me back immediately.

selectedmemories.Title: We Are The Champions - Remastered 2011
selectedmemories.description: The song reminds me of several things that all took place in the year the song was released. On that year, I moved to a different area for the first time in my life, the car factory in the town I was leaving closed, and a bird sanctuary in the place I was moving to opened. I also recall that the weather that winter was particularly harsh, mostly due to frost.

selectedmemories.Title: Fields Of Fire
selectedmemories.description: My friend and I were 13 and it was the first song that we heard on the radio that made us go "Wow!". We begged our parents to let us see them play live in Glasgow and it was the first live music concert we attended. The sight of the crowd bouncing to the music, the incredible noise from the band, the feeling of the music literally resonating within your body is still a visceral and almost tangible memory. It defined my love of live music and every concert I remember this.

selectedmemories.Title: The Story of the Blues [Part One]
selectedmemories.description: Song reminds me of my early teenage years and associated angst and troubles and as I got older. It reminds me of youth in general and my sister also said it reminds her of me.

selectedmemories.Title: Bridge Over Troubled Water
selectedmemories.description: Reminds me of my grandad when we would spend the afternoon together in his garden. He always had that song playing and when he died, I played it nonstop.

selectedmemories.Title: Wannabe
selectedmemories.description: Sitting at home watching a morning television show and this girl band performing the song. Wondering what I'd just heard, knowing it was going to be the start of something big and rushing out to buy the single.

selectedmemories.Title: Last Christmas
selectedmemories.description: I remember sitting by the tree at Christmas as it is being played.

selectedmemories.Title: Wish You Were Here-2
selectedmemories.description: At 17 my best friend was killed when I found out this was being played. Stayed with me since.

selectedmemories.Title: All My Life
selectedmemories.description: It was one of the songs that me and my now husband danced to on a night out about 15 years ago. We were in a restaurant where we had gone for a meal but there was also a dancing area and he asked me to dance when the song played. It was a very emotional time for me and every time I hear the song it takes me back to that night.

selectedmemories.Title: Thank You
selectedmemories.description: This song was the one my husband and I had our first dance to on our wedding day. It had been a big hit earlier that year, so I have a lot of memories of hearing it at work, in the car, and on the radio, but now, when I hear it I associate it with our wedding.

selectedmemories.Title: Maneater
selectedmemories.description: I was travelling round the Greek islands with a friend, and we had both finished university. We were young and had no responsibilities. We met lots of like-minded people on our trip, staying in places for as long or as little as we liked. We went out every evening to bars and clubs to go dancing and this song was always playing.

selectedmemories.Title: Liebestraum
selectedmemories.description: It was the favourite song of my grandad and a song that I played for him on the piano. It evokes memories of me playing it and seeing him closing his eyes listening to it. It brings back very happy memories for me.

selectedmemories.Title: Never Alone
selectedmemories.description: When my father was very ill just before he passed and was unconscious, we had a Spotify playlist on. Dad was a lover of Irish music and folk. This song came on, and when I heard it, it hit me hard. The first lines go "May the angels protect you, troubles neglect you, and heaven expect you when it's time to go home .." I remember crying quietly, my heart breaking, at the beauty of the words and Sean's voice. When my sisters arrived, I told them about it and we listened to it together, weeping.

selectedmemories.Title: Yesterday Once More
selectedmemories.description: When I first heard this song, I was in high school. As a teenager there were a lot of emotional things happening at that time. We studied mixed with girls and boys together. What was the most favourite thing at that time? Sure, for everyone can know. Pure friendship or love was the best thing in our memories.

selectedmemories.Title: Welcome To The Machine - 2011 Remaster
selectedmemories.description: I was at home in my living room with a parent nearby speakers turned up dancing moving around completely transported to another place. It was the first time I remember music completely taking over myself in such a powerful immersive and epic way.

selectedmemories.Title: Sweet Dreams (Are Made of This) - Remastered
selectedmemories.description: I first heard it at a club in London with a few good friends, and when I think of the song or hear it, it always reminds me of a very happy experience and those particular friends. Interestingly the song reminds me more of one of the friends who I don't see any more than a friend who I still see regularly.

selectedmemories.Title: House of the Rising Sun
selectedmemories.description: I had just been given a guitar and was trying to work out how to play the chords.

selectedmemories.Title: Don't Leave Me This Way (with Sarah Jane Morris)
selectedmemories.description: This was my nightclub song in the 80s. I always did a silly dance to it with my best friend, who is still my best friend, and the DJ who played it is still a friend over 35 years later.

selectedmemories.Title: DARE
selectedmemories.description: It reminds me of my childhood and my father as he often listened to this song and this artist. Specifically, I remember driving to a holiday in France in our family car and this song playing in the car. I was with my parents and my two older sisters.

selectedmemories.Title: Le vent nous portera
selectedmemories.description: I was lying down on the sofa in the family living room, sometime early evening. My parents were either in the kitchen next door or one of them was on the sofa next to me. I remember feeling suddenly a little melancholic, which I had never experienced with a song before, but also very aware of the feeling all of a sudden - which had not happened before either.

selectedmemories.Title: City Of Stars (Humming)
selectedmemories.description: It was the middle of the night on a weekend in September. I was with my friends Steven, Chloe, and Nathan. Together we were sat at old piano in a chapel on the edge of a lake in the middle of the North shore (arctic) woods. Nathan played the song on the piano and while I sang with him. We used the light from Steven's digital camera to see the piano keys. Nathan and I were wearing the same forest green sweatshirt. Steven was wearing the same one in light blue, and Chloe was wearing one in beige.

selectedmemories.Title: Baker Street
selectedmemories.description: I was seven years old at the time. My dad and my brother were in the back garden building a shed. I had just learned to ride my bike at that time and that afternoon we were going to Heathrow Airport to watch the planes landing and taking off. I remember feeling excited and happy and the song Baker Street was playing in the background.

selectedmemories.Title: Rock! Rock! (Till You Drop)
selectedmemories.description: With three other tenors from the school choir in a hall linked to one of the friends' houses. We were headbanging to the music drinking Pepsi.

selectedmemories.Title: The Last Waltz
selectedmemories.description: At social events in the 1970's with my family. It was always the last song to be played and I was waltzed with my parents or sang along with my family.

selectedmemories.Title: Daydream Believer
selectedmemories.description: Soft summer days during summer holidays, warm sun and friends, a time before life was disrupted by family dynamics that tore the family apart. The end of childhood and start of early adulthood.

selectedmemories.Title: Viva Forever
selectedmemories.description: I used to go to an arcade with my dad and my older sister when I was 4. I was very young, but I remember wanting to listen to it every time my dad took me there. This song has created a vivid memory of my father every time I listen to it that will last forever.

selectedmemories.Title: I Just Called To Say I Love You
selectedmemories.description: This song takes me back to being at my family home with my mum and my brother. My mother was having an affair at the time, and this was their "special song" because they used to speak to each other on the phone when my dad was at work. I have a specific memory of hearing them on the phone when I was supposed to be in bed and my mum singing this to him on the phone.

selectedmemories.Title: Waterloo Sunset
selectedmemories.description: When this song was high in the Hit Parade and constantly aired on the radio my father was in a hospital by Waterloo Bridge in London undergoing life-threatening surgery. I would visit many evenings at the sunset hour and watch the sun setting from the perspective of Waterloo Bridge. I took the title of the song completely literally and it has always evoked strong emotions in me, usually accompanied by tears.

selectedmemories.Title: Do I Wanna Know?
selectedmemories.description: I am at the gym in Barcelona in front of the beach. It's summer, I'm on a stationary bike and I'm on my own. I'm feeling very excited, free, and happy. I'm looking at the beach, the beautiful people on their roller skates or bikes enjoying their lives. I feel a bit in love with someone and the song reminds me of him somehow. I even have associated the smell of the swimming pool, which is on the other side of the room where I am, with this song. I felt so good about my life at this moment.

selectedmemories.Title: The Shoop Shoop Song (It's In His Kiss)
selectedmemories.description: Dancing at a birthday party (mine or my sisters) in a village hall, it was a disco, my friends were there, and I think we had a clown entertainer.

selectedmemories.Title: Love Don't Cost a Thing
selectedmemories.description: I was young and felt easily influenced by strong positive female role models. Jennifer Lopez was a singer I looked up to at that time. Even though I don't feel the same way about her or her music now.  At that young age I felt positive, strong, confident, and motivated when I listened to this song. I would play it in my bedroom, and imagine I was as confident as her, especially with my body image. I actually felt the opposite. I felt empowered in my own bedroom.

selectedmemories.Title: Little White Bull
selectedmemories.description: This song takes me back to the age of about six years old. My mum would play the record on our gramophone in the front room of our home. I remember all the fun and laughter as I danced around the room pretending to be a little bull. My childhood was a very happy one, as I had loving parents. We were not well off with money, but we were loved and cared for.

selectedmemories.Title: Sleep On The Floor
selectedmemories.description: It takes me through the times I've suffered from depression and started to heal. I used to listen to this song and sing along.

selectedmemories.Title: Respect
selectedmemories.description: Attending catering college and did a weekly chart with some friends. Aretha was one of my favourite singers at the time.

selectedmemories.Title: Jealous
selectedmemories.description: This song reminds me of my recent breakup, and whenever I see my better half with her new partner...

selectedmemories.Title: Overkill
selectedmemories.description: I was 14 and at Hammersmith Odeon in 1977. My first event gig. Mum was very nervous about me going to London with a mate on the train. It was 5th November and above the set were wires and during this song fireworks flew across the wires and Phil Taylor kept hitting them with his drumsticks to move them on as the bow in the wire was above his head. What was utterly cool was when the LP came out the three photos on the back were of that gig! Happy days.

selectedmemories.Title: Echo Beach
selectedmemories.description: Group of 5 friends, in our local country pub, not sure if weekday/weekend (probably a mix), during the ages 17-20. We would always select this song to play on the jukebox. We would sing along. The song had a sad/nostalgic feeling about it that reflected our stage of life (finishing A levels and heading off to university, then coming back and meeting up during holiday time).

selectedmemories.Title: Evening Hymn
selectedmemories.description: I was alone and had just taken off on a flight to America. I had left my secure job of 18 months a few days before without certainty around what my next job would be. I was on my way to meet with a group of friends before travelling to compete in a sports event. It was my first time completely alone on a long-haul flight, and I remember feeling overwhelmed by the combination of life uncertainty, missing my family, the emotion of the music, and the sun setting out of the plane window.

selectedmemories.Title: Jack & Diane
selectedmemories.description: I remember listening to this song as a teenager and it evokes memories of the 1980's hanging out with friends and being on the verge of leaving home and working out who I was and wanted to be.

selectedmemories.Title: Young Hearts Run Free
selectedmemories.description: I always think of being on holiday in Greece at about 6 years old and having this on repeat. Singing with my friend, my mum, and her mum. I don't remember many things from childhood but a lot of the memories I do have seem to involve/be invoked by music.

selectedmemories.Title: Thriller
selectedmemories.description: I was a child hiding behind the sofa in my living room whilst my dad was watching the video for this song. My dad was ok to let me watch the video as we would sing this song together in the car when it came on the radio, but I do remember being a little afraid at first.

selectedmemories.Title: Common People
selectedmemories.description: I was sitting in a car next to my husband who was driving. We were driving home after having a nice holiday in Yorkshire. We were in motorway, and it wasn't pretty, but it was sunny and pleasant. We just enjoyed listening to this song in a car. Listening to a song while driving wasn't anything special, a part of daily life we had when we had a car (we swapped a car for e-bikes now), but I vividly remember it.

selectedmemories.Title: Lover, You Should Have Come Over - Live at JBTV, Chicago, IL - November 1994
selectedmemories.description: Paris, the summer I moved into my flat on rue Ordener. I didn't have a bed yet, so was sleeping on the sofa-bed in the living room. It's night-time. Curly shadows of the wrought iron balcony, cast by the headlights of passing cars on the street below, dance across the walls. I'm working fulltime in a restaurant, only going home to sleep, so it's a rare serene and artful moment in my busy life.

selectedmemories.Title: Skinny Love
selectedmemories.description: Being on an orchestral tour of USA & Canada, 5 weeks long, travelling on coaches from venue to venue, with colleagues.
selectedmemories.emoextra: Sense of community, self confidence, security, positivity, optimism

selectedmemories.Title: Holler
selectedmemories.description: I was a Spice Girls fan when I was a young child. With a small group of friends from school, we decided to each be one of the Spice Girls and put on a show for an upcoming birthday party. We would lip sync and dance to several of their songs, and we rehearsed for weeks. This was one of my favourite songs.

selectedmemories.Title: As Usual
selectedmemories.description: I was walking along the Semedelska Cesta promenade in Koper, Slovenia. I was with my mother and my grandpa. I was rollerblading while listening to the song on my mp3 player. It was sunny, and we were by the sea.

selectedmemories.Title: Dancing in the Moonlight
selectedmemories.description: This song takes me back to the silent disco at 2011 Reading Festival. I was with my 2 school friends, and we were dancing to this in one of the performance tents. I remember taking off my headphones and laughing at all the people dancing to nothing. I also remember looking at the night sky and thinking "aw this is lovely!".

selectedmemories.Title: Sugar, Sugar
selectedmemories.description: A family party on Boxing Day in the 1970's. I remember watching all the grown-ups dancing and singing along and I felt very happy in that moment. There were Christmas decorations everywhere, we were in my Grandads house (who I loved very much!) and there was party food. Lots of my cousins were there also. Everything felt good in that moment and I felt loved and very much a part of something great.

selectedmemories.Title: Р'РёРґРµР»Рё РЅРѕС‡СЊ
selectedmemories.description: I remember this being on one of the CDs my dad had; I used to listen to the whole album on that CD and that song was my favourite. I was dancing to it and thinking that it was so much better that the other songs on that CD!

selectedmemories.Title: Walking On Sunshine
selectedmemories.description: We made a video of my daughter's first two years of life which included various clips and photos to the music of the song.

selectedmemories.Title: Blinded By The Light
selectedmemories.description: When I hear that song, I always think of walking the mile or so to secondary school each day with my sister. There was one particular corner that when we turned it - if there were no clouds - then the sun would suddenly be right in our eyes. We would then burst into song singing 'Blinded by the light'! Remembering that also makes me think of how we were always slightly late and would stretch up on our toes as we passed certain shops / offices to check their clocks for the time!

selectedmemories.Title: Dosed
selectedmemories.description: The song reminds me of my dad. The first time I heard it I was in the car with my dad and my siblings, and we were driving home.

selectedmemories.Title: Sweet
selectedmemories.description: It is more about the feeling and the state I was when listening to this song. It feels like I am transported to that period of my life when I listen to it. It is related to a period of my life when I had a long-distance relationship with someone. It reminds me of the melancholic feeling of missing this person and the excitement of trying to meet them. I even feel chills in my body, like experiencing these feelings in reality again.

selectedmemories.Title: Do They Know It's Christmas? - 1984 Version
selectedmemories.description: It was Christmas Eve and I was in the living room in the flat I grew up in. Before the relatives' arrival, my family and I made Christmas cookies, and we had the Christmas songs from my favourite CD (called Superstar Christmas) in the background. At a certain point, "Do they know it's Christmas" started. I left the biscuit dough on the table and started dancing and jumping around the living room table, which becomes in my in my childhood imagination a stage full of colours, fun and happiness.

selectedmemories.Title: Famous Blue Raincoat
selectedmemories.description: My memory is of being sad and alone as a young man soon after I moved to London. I shared a small single bedsit room with a friend in Earls Court. He worked different shifts, so I was often alone. It was cold and dark most of the time and I was thousands of miles away from home and family. It is a miserable song, but it helped me as I could identify with the singer/composer's feelings.

selectedmemories.Title: Christmas Lights
selectedmemories.description: This song reminds me of being in my first year of university, towards the end of the Christmas term and feeling very isolated/uncertain of continuing with my course. I remember listening to it walking along the streets in Exeter back to my dorm room, feeling disconnected from the festivities but something in the mood of this song resonated with me. I was desperate to get back to my family for the Christmas break and I recall that feeling every time I have heard this song since then.

selectedmemories.Title: We Found Love
selectedmemories.description: I was at an alternative music festival with my friends, and the day 3 was drawing to an end. We were at the food court hunting for a late-night bite when this song, massive hit at the time, came from the tiny radio of one of the food trucks. My friend, not your biggest music connoisseur, screamed "OMG I LOVE THIS SONG", dropped everything and started dancing like never before. It was hilarious and contagious, and we and people around us joined her.

selectedmemories.Title: Stick Season
selectedmemories.description: It brings up the memory of singing it at karaoke multiple times with the same person and a slightly different set of people each time. the person I always sang it with was the same, but the others were classmates and friends on different occasions. The first occasion was on campus, the next at a friend's accommodation, and another on campus and the last time at a different accommodation.

selectedmemories.Title: Sky and Sand
selectedmemories.description: I was dancing alone in the flat I last lived with my dad. I was in the living room, wearing a tee-shirt and pants. I was crying because the song reminded me of my dad, who had recently passed away, because I was listening to Paul Kalkbrenner with him often.

selectedmemories.Title: Toyboy
selectedmemories.description: I am outside my neighbour's house, in the summer, having just knocked and asked his mum if he could come out and play.

selectedmemories.Title: Red
selectedmemories.description: I was on a school trip to the mountains when this song came out. The leaves were just starting to change colours and that cosiness of fall really invoked the energy of the song. I was in my hotel room with my classmates prepping for a presentation the next day, listening to this song.

selectedmemories.Title: How Do You Do?
selectedmemories.description: My childhood street. Running around with my friends in downtown Annapolis, Md.; right before dusk as the fireflies a.k.a "lightening bugs" illuminated the city streets. Even now, this song (and the - literally - hundreds more from my youth) evoke such strong memories, it makes my eyes water.These songs bring back "fond" childhood memories (from a less than stellar childhood.) These tunes conjure memories I strived for...and it helped maintain happiness in tough times.

selectedmemories.Title: Million Miles Away
selectedmemories.description: Burning compilation CD disks on my bedroom PC from tracks downloaded illegally from file-sharing websites. Young/Mid teenage years and just getting into the guitar. Opening my ears to different music styles and using a very specific Marantz hifi system setup by my dad.

selectedmemories.Title: Billie Jean
selectedmemories.description: Reminds me of my childhood - key stage 2.

selectedmemories.Title: So Sick
selectedmemories.description: I was on a bus on the way to a school trip with all my classmates.

selectedmemories.Title: Yo Te Necesito
selectedmemories.description: This song reminds me of driving home with my parents and sisters after our Sunday "outing": church, grocery shopping, eating dinner. It's golden hour and the smell of the leftovers mixed with my mom's perfume fills the car.

selectedmemories.Title: Proud Mary
selectedmemories.description: When I was a child, my family would drive from the Bay Area ( San Francisco) to Southern California ( Agoura hills) . My mother and I would sing the song "Proud Mary" in the car.

selectedmemories.Title: THINGS & SUCH
selectedmemories.description: I was very high with a few close ones on Halloween 2021 dancing on the sofa at 4am to this song on repeat, it felt like I was truly experiencing music for the first time which shifted my perspective on creativity and exactly how much feeling can be induced via music & moments.

selectedmemories.Title: Alarm
selectedmemories.description: My mother was driving my best friend and me to our dance lesson. Specifically, during those months when the sunset was early so it was already dark out. We drove through the city to get to the studio. The song was playing on the radio. I then kept playing it myself on future drives to dance class for a while.

selectedmemories.Title: Futurism
selectedmemories.description: I remember listening to this song while going to take the bus to go to university. The morning of my memory is cold, and I really didn't want to go.

selectedmemories.Title: Cheerleader (Felix Jaehn Remix) - Radio Edit
selectedmemories.description: When I hear this song, it brings me back to around 2015, like the Musically era, and it reminds of how it'd often be sunny outside when this song is playing and is always a vibe to sing with family.

selectedmemories.Title: Viva La Vida
selectedmemories.description: When I think of Viva La Vida, I am reminded of my 30-minute-long drive to LeRoy Martin Middle School with my dad in his gray Honda Civic. We'd listen to the radio station "Mix 101.5," and the song was popular at the time so it came on often. My dad could never get the words right so I'd have to articulate them very clearly while I was signing along and then repeat them to him afterwards. Eventually, when the song came on during our drive, he was able to sing along to all the words.

selectedmemories.Title: American Pie
selectedmemories.description: I'm standing in the dining hall named Sbiza at Texas A&M. I'm with friends I've made at summer camp: Callum, Adam, Sophie, Mark, Kayla, Sabrina, Natalie, Leah. We're all crying bittersweet tears holding each other. We then dance in a circle while still sobbing.

selectedmemories.Title: Ride
selectedmemories.description: Reminds me of when I was looking after my little brother when my mum was busy and my dad was at work. I'd usually put the music channel on and he liked listening to Twenty One Pilots when he was younger.

selectedmemories.Title: Still Don't Know My Name
selectedmemories.description: Me and my best friend woke up at 4 in the morning and went to a park to watch the sunrise. We had a picnic and put music on. This song always reminds me of that memory because it was both of our favourite song. Especially the line "I'm dreaming of all of the possibilities".

selectedmemories.Title: Immortals
selectedmemories.description: Sitting on the carpet in my grandad's house in the spare bedroom for the grandkids with my brother next to me on his PlayStation 4. I was wearing earphones and drawing when the song came on for the first time.

selectedmemories.Title: 1812 Overture
selectedmemories.description: I was playing this music with the National Children's Orchestra. One of the first 'big' pieces that I played. I loved playing the piece and I also loved the music. It was made even more special because I was playing it with friends. The concert was in a huge concert hall which my family came to.

selectedmemories.Title: I Found
selectedmemories.description: I was in a van in Vietnam during summer many years ago. I was with my family and we were driving out of the resort to go into Hoi An and visit the market.

selectedmemories.Title: Hello
selectedmemories.description: I was only a toddler, with my parents and grandparents in the car and the song was playing. We were all singing and I was dancing, moving my feet around in the seat. I remember my Nanna and my mum laughing non-stop about my singing and dancing.

selectedmemories.Title: Tek It
selectedmemories.description: I was sitting at one of the desks in my sixth form just relaxing and I had my eyes closed and I was reminiscing about the good times I had with my ex-best friends. I was resting my head on the table. I was by myself.

selectedmemories.Title: The Great Escape
selectedmemories.description: I was at home, back in Madrid. I was in the living room sitting on the sofa with my cousin and we were doing Karaoke to this song. I recorded us singing and sent it to a close friend of mine at that time. We were alone at home and we just sang until we got tired.

selectedmemories.Title: Riptide
selectedmemories.description: I was listening to this song a lot in autumn several years ago. I used to be a ballroom dancer back then, and me and my partner danced "Quickstep" with this song, so I really enjoyed it.

selectedmemories.Title: Come As You Are
selectedmemories.description: I was with my boyfriend in the car driving down backroads at sunset screaming the song at the top of our lungs.

selectedmemories.Title: I'm Fine
selectedmemories.description: I remember being on the beach by myself, and I was alone and it was cold but I didn't have anywhere else to go.

selectedmemories.Title: Love Lies (with Normani)
selectedmemories.description: I listened to it while standing at a bus stop at around 7am. It was on either a Saturday or a Sunday and I was on my way to work. The lyrics reminded me of my feelings towards a guy I started seeing. It made me feel happy.

selectedmemories.Title: Como Antes
selectedmemories.description: I was in my room by myself revising for my A levels. This song reminds me of how I was struggling, and I think this was after an argument. At this point in my studies, I genuinely thought I wouldn't be able to pass my exams.

selectedmemories.Title: Angel
selectedmemories.description: with my best friend in KL, Malaysia. we we're just talking and vaping. we were preparing to go out for the night with some family friends.

selectedmemories.Title: Never Say Never
selectedmemories.description: Me and my sisters when we were young used to sing this all the time after watching karate kid.

selectedmemories.Title: Candy Eyes
selectedmemories.description: I was sitting on a park bench with somebody who was at the time my best friend. I had met up with them in the park late in the afternoon as I'd been out after having a personal familial conflict in the morning. Either when we were walking through the park or whilst sat at the bench (I don't remember) I had one earbud in and was listening to the album that the song is from. The sky was overcast, and it was raining a little. We didn't talk about anything unusual. The area of the park was quiet.

selectedmemories.Title: less of you
selectedmemories.description: I heard this song at a concert in the Eventim Apollo, it makes me think about how cramped it was in the standing area. I was with a girl I met at the concert. there was lots of smoke from the smoke machine appearing on stage.

selectedmemories.Title: Gracious
selectedmemories.description: I am sat in the car with my mum, dad and little brother. We are driving up to Scotland from London to visit my grandparents. It is springtime and starting to get dark. I am sat behind my dad who is driving my brother is next to me. we are both in our pyjamas with blankets because our parents want us to fall asleep.

selectedmemories.Title: From Nowhere
selectedmemories.description: On a family holiday on an island in a really fancy resort, Shangri-La, Phuket Thailand. The song was on repeat whilst we cycled around a lake, hung out in the resort, sat by the pool, during breakfast buffet. We went to the shops next door to a fancy hipster cafe that served chemistry lab themed drinks in beakers etc.

selectedmemories.Title: I Can't Go for That (No Can Do)
selectedmemories.description: This song takes me back to a pub party that was with our two friends and my mum. We drank and danced all night and had a really great time and this song was the one that made us initially get up and dance and set the night off. I also think of the pinball machines we played on and the interior and exterior of the pub (benches and how cold it was that night) and makes me think of home as the pub is very local. We also met and made loads of new friends.

selectedmemories.Title: Mayonaise - 2011 Remaster
selectedmemories.description: Reminds me of summer when I watched season 2 of "The summer I turned pretty", it was played in one of the scenes and I kept listening to this song on repeat during this season.

selectedmemories.Title: Not Guilty (feat. Tiggs Da Author & Mark Morrison)
selectedmemories.description: Getting my first car.

selectedmemories.Title: Clair de lune
selectedmemories.description: I used to listen to this music a lot while walking back alone to my dorm after a night study session when I was inschool in the Netherlands. The school was located in countryside and so surrounded by beautiful nature. The memory of the dark sky, adorned with stars and moonlight, is still vivid whenever I close my eyes.

selectedmemories.Title: Time To Rest Your Weary Head
selectedmemories.description: It was a difficult time in my life. School and family life were falling apart around me and I arrived home exhausted every day. I looked to this song alone for comfort and put it on loop to try and complete my schoolwork.

selectedmemories.Title: Hard To Explain
selectedmemories.description: On a boat, in Barbados, my boyfriend said he loved me for the first time.

selectedmemories.Title: Dance Monkey
selectedmemories.description: I was in a swimming pool in Turkey and they were playing that song while we were swimming . I was with my sister

selectedmemories.Title: A la pГЄche aux moules
selectedmemories.description: My dad would sing me this song when I was in bed to put me to sleep.

selectedmemories.Title: Get You The Moon (feat. SnГёw)
selectedmemories.description: I was on the phone with my boyfriend at the time, and we were just talking to each other about life and memories from our childhood. We deemed this song in that moment to be ours as we both helped each other with our own struggles during that time and we both could relate to that song.

selectedmemories.Title: ж€‘жѓі
selectedmemories.description: Listening to this song reminds me of how every time after junior high school, I would go to the Starbucks near school to do my homework until the evening. After finishing writing, I passed by a snack shop on the way to the subway station, and the smell inside left a deep impression on me.

selectedmemories.Title: Liability
selectedmemories.description: It reminds me of majority of my childhood as well as my romantic experiences in general. I am not someone I consider "easy" to deal with. I feel as though a lot who know me would agree since I'm never mentally here. The song sticks because it's very similar to how I perceive myself.

selectedmemories.Title: Bohemian Rhapsody
selectedmemories.description: Me, my girlfriend at the time and my friends Malik and Evie, were driving away from London on the motorway, to visit my friends' dad's cottage. Evie's dad was driving, we were all busy singing Queen from the top of our lungs. He proceeded to roll down all the windows and pass out a few joints he had rolled. We were all big smokers at the time, and we enjoyed them while hanging out the windows while still singing. This was the start of one of my favourite weekends in my life.

selectedmemories.Title: Super Rich Kids
selectedmemories.description: In the summer of 2019 through to the summer of 2020, my mental health was at some of the lowest it's ever been, and in my area there is a massive culture of drug use especially in younger teens. From a too early age I was abusing drugs amongst upper class privileged children in empty houses of parents who didn't care enough to be there. The song mirrors my experience entirely, I discovered it during this period and it's hard to think that when I saw the comparisons to my life then it felt good.

selectedmemories.Title: и€ћгЃ„иђЅгЃЎг‚‹иЉ±гЃіг‚‰пј€Fallin' Flowerпј‰
selectedmemories.description: This song reminds me of a time during COVID, where I felt a little blue and sad. I was probably listening to this song in bed, wearing my headphones.

selectedmemories.Title: Dolphin Diver
selectedmemories.description: Every time I listen to this song, I can feel a great sense of calmness. It is like a form of escapism, traveling timelessly beneath the deep sea. I can do nothing physically while listening to it. I just close my eyes, which try to close the external world and shift to the inner self-spirit. Sometimes tears come out from my eyes accompanied with an implicit emotion. When I listen to it, no one is with me, and I fully enjoy the solitude.

selectedmemories.Title: Another Brick In The Wall, Pt. 2 - 2011 Remastered Version
selectedmemories.description: I remember I was coming back from school, walking in Cromwell Road when I first heard the song. Ironically there was a brick wall alongside the pedestrian path under which there was the Underground railway. I very much liked the song and intentionally elongated my walk to continue listening to it once more. The second time I managed to repeat (while listening) parts of its lyrics that I liked. I remember the weather was cloudy and cold, during winter. Since then the song reminds me that location.

selectedmemories.Title: On the Level
selectedmemories.description: I was in my old bedroom, which is quite nostalgic to me now, revisiting one of my favourite videogames that I've played on and off for around 7 years. Though, this time was the first where I had really started to become interested in the lore, and the quests I was completing, not just progressing the story or collecting items. I was going through a rough period in the relationship I was in at the time, and the immersion was a welcome escape. It's a fond memory, and I had the song on repeat.

selectedmemories.Title: You Should Be Dancing
selectedmemories.description: This song was in the first pantomime I performed in as a child. It takes me back to that Christmas, the run of shows, the smell of the theatre and the people on the dance team. I can still remember the choreography; this was about 20 years ago !

selectedmemories.Title: Chalte Chalte - Part 1 / From "Chalte Chalte"
selectedmemories.description: I was back home on vacation, my father & uncle were singing this song because they love it, and I was on the couch lying down with my head on my mother's lap - I was feeling super sick & crampy that day. My dad & uncle aren't even good singers but their singing just made me tear up.

selectedmemories.Title: Gimme! Gimme! Gimme! (A Man After Midnight)
selectedmemories.description: Song was one of several used for a dance performance for a friend's wedding. Me and five other friends practiced over a few months. The song is mostly associated with those practice sessions and the people involved. We practiced and performed in different places so the association to a place is not very strong.

selectedmemories.Title: Mask Off
selectedmemories.description: I remember being at a UNC/Duke game as a college junior where Michael Jordan made a surprise appearance. UNC won the game and became regular season champions.

selectedmemories.Title: Bohemian Rhapsody
selectedmemories.description: When I was young, I wanted to be Freddie Mercury or perhaps Roger Taylor (Queen's drummer). I grew up in a small village in England but the huge camp glitz of Queen's DVD of their music videos and Live Aid was the perfect stimulus to my imagination. That music rocks my heart.

selectedmemories.Title: Flickering
selectedmemories.description: It reminds me of having the lights off, only a string of fairy lights leaving a faint glow against the objects in my room. I like this song because it makes the room feel large, echoing against the walls. I felt at peace knowing that for the rest of the night, I could be alone with my music and thoughts. There was not a single thing I had to do, and I felt deeply at ease. Normally, I would light an incense stick and feel the hardwood against my bare feet. Then a deep sleep.

selectedmemories.Title: Me Gustas Tu
selectedmemories.description: I don't remember how old I was, probably in primary school. It was summer, I was at my grandma's because my aunt living in the USA was visiting us. I remember she showed us this album and also brought us some nazar amulets from her stop in Turkey or Greece. I really love my aunt and whenever she was coming to Romania, it was very exciting because she was always bringing us gifts.
selectedmemories.emoextra: not sure if they are emotions but Curiosity, Playfullness, Ease, Discovery

selectedmemories.Title: Fly Like An Eagle
selectedmemories.description: I'm listening to this song in the backseat of a car while my dad is driving. I can't be more than 4 years old. The car is a sedan, with cloth interior seating. My parents are separated, and I am visiting my dad in Spain. I can remember getting in the car, pulling out of the driveway, and hearing this song on the radio. It soon became a favourite of mine. I don't know if this is the first time I had heard the song, but I feel like it was. I don't have any other real memories from this time period.
